key_insights: When financials (XLF) stop making new highs while the market makes new all-time highs, it's an indicator that the market is probably getting close to the top
Always look at the banks - if the banks don't keep going higher, then the market ultimately will not keep going up because you need the liquidity
Hope is not a strategy - don't sit and do nothing during pullbacks
Buying on margin creates double risk - you lose on your capital AND the borrowed money, effectively doubling your losses
When QQQ makes new all-time highs but SPY does not, it can indicate the market is potentially going to roll over
Go long at a price level or go short at the trend - use these levels for entries
Don't buy the banks after big rallies when valuations are too high and price-to-tangible book value is unsustainable

summary: Bill Fanter's October 13th watchlist focuses on the importance of monitoring financial sector weakness as a leading indicator for market tops. He discusses how all major banks peaked around September 23rd while the market continued making new highs, signaling the recent selloff. He emphasizes the dangers of margin trading after Friday's crypto liquidation event and provides specific price levels to watch for major indices and bank stocks heading into earnings week.
